            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old retired civil engineer who lives with his wife of 46 years in a quiet suburban neighborhood. He is a tall, slightly stooped man with a weathered complexion, thinning silver hair, and mild muscle wasting noticeable in his arms and shoulders. He presents with a 4-month history of progressive fatigue, unintentional weight loss of approximately 8 kg, intermittent lower abdominal cramping, and a change in bowel habits alternating between constipation and loose stools. He reports occasional blood-streaked stools, which he initially attributed to hemorrhoids and delayed seeking medical attention.\n\n{patientName} spent over 35 years working in civil engineering, much of which involved desk work and occasional fieldwork. Since retiring at 65, he enjoys woodworking in his garage, tending his vegetable garden, and attending his local church choir. He is an avid reader and spends evenings watching history documentaries. He is socially active, meeting weekly with a small group of friends for coffee, though he admits he has felt too tired to attend recently.\n\nHis diet has historically been low in fiber and high in red and processed meats — a habit formed during decades of long working hours and convenience eating. He drinks approximately two glasses of red wine per week and quit smoking 20 years ago after a 25 pack-year history. He exercises lightly, taking short daily walks, though his activity has declined over the past few months due to fatigue and discomfort.\n\n{patientName} is visibly anxious about his diagnosis, and his wife, who accompanies him to all appointments, is equally distressed. He is cooperative and engaged but admits to feeling a sense of denial about the severity of his condition. His appetite has diminished notably, and he reports feeling full quickly after small meals. He denies nausea, vomiting, or jaundice, but notes occasional night sweats over the past six weeks.\n\nHe has three adult children and six grandchildren who live nearby and are closely involved in his care. {patientName} is motivated to pursue treatment and has expressed a desire to discuss all available options with his oncology team. He values his independence and quality of life above all."
